column1: Define software architectural development constraints and resources
column21: The constraints on the architecture development and the resources available for the development of the software and the software architecture need to be understood before beginning development of the architecture. Analyze the system and subsystem constraints and project software development schedule to determine how they impact the architecture development. Identify the list of existing architectural assets that are available for reuse. Review the make/buy/GFE/CFE plan to understand decisions that have already been made that impact the architecture.

column21:
Multiple views are required to represent the software architecture. The specific views depend on the nature of the software system being developed. There are a few standard view sets to choose from, including Kruchten’s 4+1 and SEI Documenting Software Architecture, Views and Beyond styles. It is not required to follow any particular set, but it is necessary to show different, relevant, and needed views of the architecture. Explicitly identify the granularity and level of detail of elements to be captured in each architecture view. The scope and objectives of the software architecture, constrained by the development schedule and make/buy plan, shall be used to identify the list of architectural views that will be specified for the software architecture.



Additional views, such as security and data views, should be used to represent the functional, non-functional, data communication, and trust boundaries of the architecture.

 * Associated Directives: SW-Arch-DPP.003, SW-Arch-DPP.004

column1: Update feasibility discriminators for the architectural solutions
column21:
Determine which criteria are mandatory and represent feasibility discriminators for the architectural solutions. Determine which characteristics and requirements are most critical for success across the life cycle of the end-item. The highest priority criteria exert the most influence on the architecture decisions.



The system constraints that impact the software architecture shall be identified as architectural constraints. Consideration should be given to the system/subsystem constraints, software requirements, constraints on architecture development, and key architecture requirements and how they impact the software architecture. The constraints can bound the types of architectures that can be considered and the architectural assets that can be reused.

 * SW-Arch-DPP.002

column21:
The architecture shall be evaluated using an architecture review method that evaluates how well the architecture meets its objectives, constraints, and quality attributes. The architecture can be evaluated by using scenarios that exercise the critical quality attributes. The SEI’s Architecture Tradeoff and Analysis Method (ATAM) is an approach for evaluating architectures.



Perform a software architecture security risk assessment by identifying weaknesses susceptible to attack, the likelihood of an attack, potential impact, and requirements for mitigation to reduce the risk. The architecture can be assessed by using attack scenarios that exploit the operational scenarios and software architecture weaknesses. This activity may result in additional software security requirements and constraints.

 * Associated Directives: SW-Arch-DPP.0017
